<section>
<title>Variance and Standard Deviation of a Discrete Random Variable</title>
<body>
<p>In Exploratory Data Analysis, we used the mean of a sample of quantitative values (their
                    arithmetic average<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T151335-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mover accent="true">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                            </m:mrow>
                            <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                        </m:mover>
                    </m:math>) to tell the center of their distribution, and the standard deviation
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T151331-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>s<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T151332-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    to tell the typical distance of sample values from their mean. We
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T151625-0500"?>described<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T151623-0500" content="tell"?>
                    the center of a probability distribution for a random variable by reporting its
                    mean <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:msub>
                            <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:msub>
                    </m:math>, and now we would like to establish an accompanying measure of spread.
                    Our measure of spread will still report the typical distance of values from
                    their
                    mean<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T151645-0500"?>s<?oxy_insert_end?>,
                    but in order to distinguish the spread of a population of all of a random
                    variable's values from the spread
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T151655-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>s<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T151657-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    of sample values, we will denote the standard deviation of the random variable X
                    with the Greek lower case "sigma," and use a subscript to remind us what is the
                    variable of interest (there may be more than one in later problems):</p>
</body>
</section>
