</m:math> rather than standard deviation <m:math overflow="scroll">
<m:msub>
<m:mi>σ</m:mi>
<m:mrow>
<m:mi>X</m:mi>
</m:mrow>
</m:msub>
</m:math>.</p>
<example><title>Xavier's Production Line</title>

<p>Recall that the number of defective parts produced each hour by Xavier's production line is a random variable X with the following probability distribution:</p>
<image style="block" src="../webcontent/image012.gif" alt="A probability distribution table with two rows, labeled &quot;X&quot;
and &quot;P(X=x).&quot; The data in column format (X: P(X=x)):
        0: .15;
        1: .30;
        2: .25;
        3: .20;
        4: .10;"/>
<p>We found the mean number of defective parts produced per hour to be <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                                <m:mrow>
                                    <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                                </m:mrow>
                            </m:msub>
                        </m:math><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T151814-0500"?>
                        <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T151815-0500"?>
                        <?oxy_insert_end?>1.8. Obviously, there is variation about this mean: some
                        hours as few as 0 defective parts are produced, whereas in other hours as
                        many as 4 are produced. Typically, how far does the number of defective
                        parts fall from the mean of 1.8? As we did for the spread of sample values,
                        we measure the spread of a random variable by calculating the square root of
                        the average squared deviation from the mean. Now "average" is a weighted
                        average, where more probable values of the random variable are accordingly
                        given more weight. Let's begin with the variance, or average squared
                        deviation from the mean, and then take its square root to find the standard
                        <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T152313-0500" comment="consider adding asterisks to indicate multiplication, and making sure there is a space between &quot;+&quot; or &quot;-&quot; and the numerals or parentheses, in the variance equation below -- simply relying on &quot;proximity&quot; to indicate mulitplication can be confusing when superscripts and multiple parentheses are involved."?>deviation:<?oxy_comment_end?></p>
<image style="block" src="../webcontent/image033.gif" alt="A table describing for several characteristics
of of possible values of X. For X=0, Dev. from mean = (0-1.8), Sq. deviation = (0-1.8)&sup2;, and P(X=0)
